data.content:
Your code doesn't actually use `Thread.Abort()`, `Thread.ResetAbort()`, `Thread.Interrupt()`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically in .NET 8. No migration is needed for Thread.Abort concerns.

That said, for modern .NET you'd benefit from replacing the manual thread management with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll`:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        await Task.Delay(100, ct);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

This gives you built-in cancellation support via `CancellationToken` and better resource usage through the thread pool.
